  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Local organic results</strong> are the traditional blue-link search listings that appear below the local pack on Google for location-based queries. They blend standard SEO signals — content quality, backlinks, authority — with local relevance factors like geographic content, NAP consistency, and local landing pages. BrightLocal research shows they capture 35% of all local search clicks.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Click share</div>
            <div class="tms-value">35% of local search clicks</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Primary signal</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Website content + local relevance</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most local SEO attention goes to the local pack — the map with three business listings. The businesses building dominant local search presence understand that local organic results below the pack represent a second category of visibility that most competitors ignore.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are local organic results?</h2>
        <p>Local organic results are the standard blue hyperlinks that Google displays below the local pack for queries with local intent. They are visually identical to regular organic results — title, URL, and meta description — but Google applies local relevance signals when deciding which pages rank for location-specific queries.</p>
        <p>When someone searches "dentist Portland," Google shows:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Paid ads (sometimes)</li>
          <li>The local pack — a map with three business listings</li>
          <li>Local organic results — blue-link website pages</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Local organic results rank based on your website, not your Google Business Profile. A business with no GBP listing can rank in local organic results if their website content is strong enough. The inverse is also true: a business can dominate the local pack while having no local organic presence.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">BrightLocal research</div>
          <p>BrightLocal's local consumer research shows that <strong>35% of all local search clicks go to local organic results</strong>, with the local pack capturing roughly 42% and paid ads taking the remainder. Appearing in both the local pack and top organic results can put a single business in front of 77% of all local search clicks for a given query.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why local organic results matter</h2>
        <p>Three reasons to invest in local organic visibility beyond the local pack:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Substantial standalone click share.</strong> 35% of local search clicks is not a rounding error. For competitive terms, those clicks represent significant monthly customer inquiries going to whoever holds those organic positions.</li>
          <li><strong>More stability than the local pack.</strong> Local pack positions fluctuate based on the searcher's exact location — a business can be position #1 from one city block and absent from the pack from another. Local organic results are more stable because they don't shift based on proximity the same way.</li>
          <li><strong>Informational queries that the pack doesn't serve.</strong> Queries like "cost of dental implants Denver" or "how long does roof replacement take in Phoenix" don't trigger a local pack. They generate organic results. Local businesses that publish content answering these questions capture informational intent that the local pack misses entirely.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How local organic results work</h2>
        <p>Google ranks pages in local organic results using a blend of standard SEO signals plus local relevance factors. The page on your website — not your GBP — is what ranks here.</p>

        <h3>Key ranking signals for local organic</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Location-specific landing pages.</strong> A dedicated page for "dentist Portland" with Portland-specific content, reviews, and location data ranks far better than a generic "services" page hoping to capture local intent.</li>
          <li><strong>NAP consistency.</strong> Your Name, Address, and Phone number appearing consistently across your website and citations signals to Google that the geographic data is reliable.</li>
          <li><strong>Local backlinks.</strong> Links from locally relevant websites — community organizations, local newspapers, chamber of commerce — contribute geographic authority to your organic rankings.</li>
          <li><strong>LocalBusiness schema.</strong> Structured data markup telling Google exactly where your business is located and what areas it serves gives Google structured confirmation of your geographic scope.</li>
          <li><strong>Local content publishing.</strong> Blog posts targeting location-specific queries expand your local organic footprint beyond service pages alone.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>The content strategy for local organic</h3>
        <p>The fastest way to grow local organic traffic is publishing location-specific content systematically:</p>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Queries local organic results capture that the pack misses</span><br>
          <span class="uf-new">"cost of dental implants in Denver"</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> informational → organic<br>
          <span class="uf-new">"best time to replace HVAC in Phoenix"</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> informational → organic<br>
          <span class="uf-new">"Austin personal injury lawsuit timeline"</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> informational → organic<br>
          <span class="uf-new">"plumber near me"</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> transactional → local pack + organic
        </div>

        <h2 id="types">Local organic vs local pack — how they differ</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Local Organic Results</th><th>Local Pack</th></tr>
            </thead>
