        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real local organic results examples</h2>

        <h3>Example 1 — Law firm, long-tail local organic expansion</h3>
        <p>A personal injury firm ranking in the local pack for "personal injury lawyer Austin" found that the pack only captured transactional queries. They built a content program targeting informational local queries — "car accident settlement amounts in Texas," "Austin intersection accident statistics," "how long personal injury cases take in Travis County." Within four months, they captured five local organic positions across these informational terms and doubled overall local search traffic without touching their GBP optimization.</p>

        <h3>Example 2 — Dental practice dominating the SERP</h3>
        <p>A Portland dental practice holding position #2 in the local pack for "dentist downtown Portland" also published local content and built location-specific service pages. The result: they appeared in both the local pack (#2) and the #1 organic result for the same query. Two visible positions on one page captured approximately 45% of all clicks — a 2x efficiency gain from the same amount of SEO investment targeting two different ranking systems.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local organic results vs the local pack — which to focus on first?</h2>
        <p>For most local service businesses, the answer is both — but the local pack is typically faster to move. Here is a practical prioritization framework:</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Prioritize local pack first when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You have a verified GBP listing</li>
              <li>You want transactional traffic quickly</li>
              <li>Your target queries are "near me" or "[service] [city]"</li>
              <li>Your website has thin content today</li>
              <li>You're in a market with 3-6 month results timelines</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Invest in local organic when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Local pack is saturated in your market</li>
              <li>You want informational query traffic</li>
              <li>You want more stable, less proximity-dependent rankings</li>
              <li>You're publishing regular local content</li>
              <li>You want page domination (pack + organic)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for local organic rankings</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Build one location page per city, not one page for all cities.</strong> A single "service areas" page trying to rank for 10 cities ranks well for none. Dedicated city pages with unique content rank for each.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish local informational content consistently.</strong> Aim for 2-4 locally relevant blog posts monthly. Each post expands your local organic footprint by targeting queries that don't trigger a local pack.</li>
          <li><strong>Add LocalBusiness schema to every location page.</strong> Structured data gives Google explicit geographic context and improves your chance of rich result features.</li>
          <li><strong>Ensure NAP is consistent sitewide.</strong> Your business name, address, and phone number should appear identically in your footer, contact page, and all location pages. Inconsistencies confuse Google's geographic attribution.</li>
          <li><strong>Build internal links from blog posts to service pages.</strong> Every blog post targeting a local informational query should link to the relevant service landing page. This passes authority and clarifies the relationship between content and conversion pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Track local organic separately from national organic.</strong> Use Google Search Console filtered by location, or set up rank tracking from within your target cities. Rankings you see from your office may not reflect what local searchers see.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — ignoring local organic while chasing the pack</div>
          <p>Many local SEO campaigns optimise exclusively for the local pack and publish no local content. When the pack becomes competitive, they have no organic presence to fall back on. The businesses that dominate local search long-term target both systems — with GBP optimization driving the pack and consistent local content building organic visibility below it.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common local organic mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>One page for all service areas</strong> — dilutes geographic signals across all target cities and ranks well for none.</li>
          <li><strong>No local content strategy</strong> — leaves informational local queries (which don't trigger the local pack) entirely to competitors.</li>
          <li><strong>Tracking rankings from your office</strong> — your office location skews local results. Track from within target cities using rank tracking tools.</li>
          <li><strong>Assuming GBP alone drives organic</strong> — your GBP has no direct effect on organic results. Website content drives organic; GBP drives the pack.</li>
          <li><strong>Missing LocalBusiness schema</strong> — pages without structured geographic data give Google less certainty about your service area, which can suppress local relevance scoring.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
